<MA5Format> Simplified LHE format </MA5Format>
<MadAnalysis5Version> 1.11.0 2025/04/23</MadAnalysis5Version>
<SampleAnalyzerVersion> 1.11.0 1.11.0 </SampleAnalyzerVersion>
<FormatDescription>
#################################################################################
# The original Les Houches Event (LHE) format is defined in hep-ph/0609017      #
#################################################################################
# The <init> ... </init> block contains global information about the samples    #
# given as a single line:                                                       #
#    IDBM1 IDBM2 EBM1 EBM2 PDFG1 PDFG2 PDFS1 PDFS1 PDFS2 IDWT NPR               #
# with:                                                                         #
#   - IDBM1: PDG code of the first beam.                                        #
#   - IDBM2: PDG code of the second beam.                                       #
#   - EBM1:  energy of the first beam.                                          #
#   - EBM2:  energy of the second beam.                                         #
#   - PDFG1: author group of the PDF employed for the first beam.               #
#   - PDFG2: author group of the PDF employed for the second beam.              #
#   - PDFS1: id of the PDF set employed for the first beam.                     #
#   - PDFS2: id of the PDF set employed for the second beam.                    #
#   - IDWT:  weighting strategy.                                                #
#   - NPR:   number of physics processes involved during the generation of      #
#            the sample.                                                        #
# The following lines give detailed process information (one line for each      #
# process):                                                                     #
#    XSEC XERR XMAX LPR                                                         #
# with:                                                                         #
#   -  XSEC: cross section                                                      #
#   -  XERR: cross section error                                                #
#   -  XMAX: maximum event weight                                               #
#   -  LPR:  process id                                                         #
#################################################################################
# Each event is described by an <event> ... </event> block. This block always   #
# starts by a single line containing general information on the event:          #
#    N IDPR XWGT SCAL AQED AQCD                                                 #
# with:                                                                         #
#   - N:    number of particles                                                 #
#   - IDPR: process id                                                          #
#   - XWGT: event weight                                                        #
#   - SCAL: scale                                                               #
#   - AQED: alpha QED                                                           #
#   - AQCD: alpha QCD                                                           #
# This line is then followed by one line for each particle in the event:        #
#    ID IST MOTH1 MOTH2 ICOL1 ICOL2 P1 P2 P3 P4 P5 VTIM SPIN                    #
# with:                                                                         #
#   - ID:    PDG code                                                           #
#   - IST:   status code                                                        #
#   - MOTH1: row number corresponding to the first mother particle              #
#   - MOTH2: row number corresponding to the second mother particle             #
#   - ICOL1: first color tag                                                    #
#   - ICOL2: second color tag                                                   #
#   - P1:    PX                                                                 #
#   - P2:    PY                                                                 #
#   - P3:    PZ                                                                 #
#   - P4:    E                                                                  #
#   - P5:    M (a space-like virtuality is denoted by a negative mass)          #
#   - VTIM:  c tau                                                              #
#   - SPIN:  cosine of the angle between the spin vector of the particle and    #
#            its three-momentum                                                 #
#################################################################################
# In the 'simplified LHE' format, there are three types of objects classified   #
# according to their statuscode:                                                #
#   - objects with StatusCode = -1: initial interacting partons.                #
#   - objects with StatusCode = +3: particles produced during the hard process. #
#   - objects with StatusCode = +1: physics objects reconstructed by a fast     #
#                                   detector simulation (or perfect detector).  #
# When MadAnalysis is in charge of the reconstruction (i.e., applying the       #
# jet-clustering algorithm), the particle codes follow the conventions:         #
#   - particle with a PDG code = +11 or -11: electrons and positrons.           #
#     They can be isolated or not as well as possibly issued from the           #
#     hadronization process.                                                    #
#   - particle with a PDG code = +13 or -13: muons and antimuons.               #
#     They can be isolated or not as well as possibly issued from the           #
#     hadronization process.                                                    #
#   - particle with a PDG code = +15 or -15: hadronically decaying (anti)taus.  #
#     These consist of jets matching a hadronically-decaying tau when           #
#     inspecting the Monte Carlo history. (Mis)Identification efficiency can be #
#     possibly included.                                                        #
#   - particle with a PDG code = 5: b-jets.                                     #
#     These consist of jets matching a b-quark when inspecting the Monte Carlo  #
#     history. (Mis)Identification efficiency can be possibly included.         #
#   - particle with a PDG code = 21: jets which are not b-tagged and taus which #
#     are not tau-tagged. The jet collection includes also electrons collection #
#     and hadronic taus collection                                              #
#   - particle with a PDG code = 12: the missing transverse energy.             #
#     The missing transverse energy is computed as opposite to the sum of the   #
#     four-momenta of all jets, electrons, muons and hadronic taus.             #
#################################################################################
</FormatDescription>
Original header:

